<P>I don't move, to have the <HI>Use</HI> of it Banished; but the <HI>Abuse</HI> and <HI>Excess</HI> of it. And I most importunately move, That all <HI>Sober People</HI> throughout the Land, would set themselves to think, <HI>What may be done, to have Rum used with more of Moderation?</HI></P>
<P>The <HI>French</HI> and the <HI>Indians</HI> have sore|ly Scourged us; but let it not be thought a <HI>Paradox,</HI> That one of the <HI>Sorest Punishments,</HI> which ever did or ever can befall this poor Country, is the <HI>Great Esteem, which this Liquor has among us.</HI> It makes us <HI>Poor;</HI> It keeps us <HI>Poor;</HI> whole <HI>Families</HI> may curse the Day, that ever the <HI>Bottel</HI> came into them. It will soon make us a <HI>D<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="faint" EXTENT="1 letter">spica|ble Country.</HI> All our <HI>Strength</HI> will be
